When Rey first uses the Force heal power on the serpent's wound, she explains to BB-8 that she simply gave it a little of her life. She uses this power a few more times throughout the film, so I think when Palpatine absorbs hers and Ben's life-force, that's why Ben is able to stand and even get back up after being thrown away and Rey isn't.

I'd like to think she isn't really automatically more powerful just because she's a Palpatine/the heroine (but then, Ben is the grandson of the Chosen One, so yeah), but I mostly took it to be that she'd already sacrificed a good chunk of her life-force by that point and she was pretty much running on empty once Palpatine drained her.

So when Ben transfers his own life into her to revive her, he has to give her all he's got, hence his death.


Like you said, life-draining is a Dark Side power and life-giving is a Light Side one, so I think it makes sense. Self-sacrifice is heroic, whereas sacrificing others is villainous. Just as Anakin sacrificed his life to save Luke, Ben sacrifices his to save Rey.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here's some reasons it was great, beyond being an entertaining movie to watch.
1) It addressed the issue of Luke's fall from grace in the previous movie by returning him to his heroic nature as a Force Ghost.
2) It addressed the canon-destroying Holdo maneuver by openly ridiculing it.
3) It explained the potential origins of the term "First Order" by introducing the "Final Order" which is a reference to order 151 of the Grand Army of the Republic - to kill Palpatine in order to preserve the eternal empire. SInce Order 1 is not known (according to wookieepedia), we can assume Order 1 or "The First Order" was something along the lines of "ensure the eternal rule of the Galactic Authority".
4) Introduced Force Dyad and Force Bonds: similar to KOTOR's Bastila Shan and Revan, I think it made a lot of sense (and fit in with extant concepts) that Rey and Ben shared a Force Bond that made each of them more powerful.
5) Mary Sue, Rey was a Palpatine, she also had a Force Bond with a Skywalker who had trained most of his life to master both sides of the force. She was not a Mary Sue: well done.
6) It did not destroy Anakin's legacy or diminish his sacrifice: he saved his son and defeated the Emperor and the Empire in the process. Nothing lasts forever, but Anakin IS and REMAINS the Chosen One, delivering peace and balance for an entire generation before evil (Palpatine) could recover and reattempt to conquer the Galaxy; an evil that eventually met its demise at the hands of his grandson and a woman who was emboldened by his children.
